{"title_page": "Vice (2018 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 American biographical drama film by Adam McKay}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Vice\n| image          = Vice (2018 film poster).png\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Adam McKay]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Brad Pitt]]\n* [[Dede Gardner]]\n* [[Jeremy Kleiner]]\n* Kevin J. Messick\n* [[Will Ferrell]]\n* Adam McKay\n}}\n| writer         = Adam McKay\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Christian Bale]]\n* [[Amy Adams]]\n* [[Steve Carell]]\n* [[Sam Rockwell]]\n* [[Tyler Perry]]\n* [[Alison Pill]]\n* [[Lily Rabe]]\n* [[Jesse Plemons]]\n}}<!--PER BILLING BLOCK http://www.impawards.com/2018/vice_ver3.html-->\n| music          = [[Nicholas Britell]]\n| cinematography = [[Greig Fraser]]\n| editing        = [[Hank Corwin]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Plan B Entertainment]]\n* [[Gary Sanchez Productions]]\n* [[Annapurna Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = Annapurna Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|12|11|[[Samuel Goldwyn Theater]]|2018|12|25|United States}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $60 million<ref>{{cite web|title=The Reasons Behind Annapurna\u2019s Tumultuous Week|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/annapurna-shakeup-reasons-james-bond-roger-ailes-jennifer-lopez-megan-ellison-analysis-1202480157/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro |date=October 10, 2018|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Annapurna>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/welcome/2702210/single/~annapurna-upheaval-megan-ellison-reevaluating-film-division~/|title=Annapurna Upheaval: Megan Ellison Is \u2018Reevaluating\u2019 Film Division Amid Money Woes|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=October 10, 2018|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $76.1 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=Vice (2018) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dickcheneyfilm.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Vice''''' is a 2018 American [[biographical film|biographical]] [[drama]] film written and directed by [[Adam McKay]]. The film stars [[Christian Bale]] as former [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Dick Cheney]],<ref name=\"Bale\">{{cite web|url=http://pagesix.com/2017/04/12/christian-bale-cast-as-dick-cheney-in-biopic/|title=Christian Bale cast as Dick Cheney in biopic|magazine=[[Page Six]]|date=April 12, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> with [[Amy Adams]], [[Steve Carell]], [[Sam Rockwell]], [[Justin Kirk]], [[Tyler Perry]], [[Alison Pill]], [[Lily Rabe]], and [[Jesse Plemons]] in supporting roles. The film follows Cheney on his path to become the most powerful [[List of vice presidents of the United States|Vice President]] in American history.<ref>{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Agar|url=https://screenrant.com/dick-cheney-biopic-george-bush-actor-cast/|title=Dick Cheney Biopic: George W. Bush Actor & More Revealed|website=[[Screen Rant]]|publisher=Valnet, Inc.|location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada|date=August 18, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Dominic|last=Patten|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/bill-pullman-dick-cheney-movie-nelson-rockefeller-casting-adam-mckay-1202154065/|title=Bill Pullman joins Jeff Bridges' Dick Cheney movie as a veep himself|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 22, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> It is the second theatrical film to depict the [[presidency of George W. Bush]], following [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[W. (film)|W.]]'' (2008).\n\n''Vice'' was released in the United States on December 25, 2018, by [[Annapurna Pictures]], and grossed $76 million worldwide. Despite the performances of the cast (particularly Bale, Adams and Rockwell) receiving universal acclaim, the film polarized critics; some considered it to be one of the best films of the year while others thought it to be one of the worst, with McKay's screenplay and direction receiving both \"scathing critiques and celebratory praise\". <ref>{{cite web|first=Nate|last=Nickolai|date=December 17, 2018|title=\u2018Vice\u2019 Reviews: What the Critics Are Saying|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/vice-reviews-critics-christian-bale-adam-mckay-1203091272|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=New York City|accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Alison|last=Foreman|date=December 17, 2018|title=\u2018VICE' divides critics in early reviews|url=https://mashable.com/article/vice-review-roundup-christian-bale-dick-cheney/#FywJb4QPPOqR|work=[[Mashable]]|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film received [[List of accolades received by Vice (2018 film)|numerous awards and nominations]], with eight nominations at the [[91st Academy Awards]], including a [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] nomination and a win for [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Make-Up and Hairstyling]]. It also had a leading six nominations at the [[76th Golden Globe Awards]] (including a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]), and six nominations at the [[72nd British Academy Film Awards]]. For their performances, Bale, Adams, and Rockwell were nominated at all three shows, with Bale winning the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]].\n\n==Plot==\n''Vice'' is narrated by Kurt, a fictitious veteran of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] and [[Iraq War]]s. The film opens with [[Dick Cheney]] and other [[White House]] officials and staff responding to the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]]. The film then flashes back to [[Wyoming]] in 1963, where Cheney finds work as a [[lineworker|lineman]] after his alcoholism led him to drop out of [[Yale University]]. After Cheney is stopped by a traffic cop for [[Driving under the influence|driving while intoxicated]], his wife [[Lynne Cheney]] convinces him to clean up his life.\n\nThe film flashes forward to 1969 when Cheney finds work as a White House intern during the [[Presidency of Richard Nixon|Nixon Administration]]. Working under Nixon's economic adviser, [[Donald Rumsfeld]], Cheney becomes a savvy political operative as he juggles commitments to his wife and their daughters, [[Liz Cheney|Liz]] and [[Mary Cheney|Mary]]. Cheney overhears [[Henry Kissinger]] discussing the secret [[Operation Menu|bombing of Cambodia]] with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Richard Nixon]], revealing the true power of the [[Federal government of the United States#Executive branch|executive branch]] to Cheney. Rumsfeld's abrasive attitude leads to him and Cheney being distanced from Nixon, which works in both men's favor; after [[Richard Nixon's resignation speech|Nixon's resignation]], Cheney rises to the position of [[White House Chief of Staff]] for President [[Gerald Ford]] while Rumsfeld becomes [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]]. The media later dubs the sudden shake-up in the [[Cabinet of the United States|cabinet]] as the [[Halloween Massacre]]. During his tenure, a young [[Antonin Scalia]] introduces Cheney to the [[unitary executive theory]].\n\nAfter [[1976 United States presidential election|Ford is voted out of office]], Cheney runs to be [[1978 United States House of Representatives election in Wyoming|representative for Wyoming]]. After giving an awkward and uncharismatic campaign speech, Cheney suffers his first [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. While he recovers, Lynne campaigns on her husband's behalf, helping him to win a seat in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]. During the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan Administration]], Cheney supported a raft of conservative, pro-business policies favoring the [[fossil fuel]] industries. He also supported the abolishment of the [[FCC fairness doctrine]] which led to the rise of [[Fox News]], [[conservative talk radio]], and the rising level of [[Political polarization|party polarization]] in the United States. Cheney next serves as [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] under President [[George H. W. Bush]] during the [[Gulf War]]. Outside of politics, Cheney and Lynne come to terms with their younger daughter, Mary, [[coming out]] as [[lesbian]]. Though Cheney develops ambitions to run for president, he decides to retire from public life to spare Mary from media scrutiny.\n\nDuring the [[presidency of Bill Clinton]], Cheney becomes the CEO of [[Halliburton]] while his wife raises [[Golden Retriever|golden retrievers]] and [[Lynne Cheney#Books|writes books]]. A false epilogue claims that Cheney lived the rest of his life healthy and happy in the private sector and credits begin rolling, only for them to abruptly end as the film continues.\n\nCheney is invited to become running mate to [[George W. Bush]] during the [[2000 United States presidential election]]. Cheney seems to feel that the younger Bush is more interested in pleasing his father than attaining power for himself, Cheney agrees on the condition that Bush delegates \"mundane\" executive responsibilities, such as [[Energy policy of the United States|energy]], the [[United States Armed Forces|military]], and [[Foreign policy of the United States|foreign policy]], to him. As [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]], Cheney works with Secretary of Defense Rumsfeld, legal counsel [[David Addington]], [[Mary Matalin]], and the [[Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States|Chief of Staff]], [[Scooter Libby]], to exercise control of key [[Foreign policy of the George W. Bush administration|foreign policy]] and defense decisions throughout Washington.\n\nThe film returns to the aftermath of the September 11 attacks, as Cheney and Rumsfeld maneuver to initiate and then preside over the U.S. invasions [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|of Afghanistan]] and [[2003 invasion of Iraq|Iraq]], resulting in the killing of hundreds of thousands of civilians and the torture of prisoners. As the [[War on terror|War on Terror]] mounts, Cheney continues to struggle with persistent heart attacks. The film also covers various events from his vice presidency, including his endorsement of the unitary executive theory, the [[Plame affair]], the [[Dick Cheney hunting accident|accidental shooting]] of [[Harry Whittington]], and tensions between the Cheney sisters over [[same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]]. Cheney's actions are shown to lead to hundreds of thousands of deaths and the rise of the [[Islamic State of Iraq]], resulting in him receiving record-low [[United States presidential approval rating|approval ratings]] by the end of the Bush administration.\n\nWhile narrating Cheney's tearful deathbed goodbye to his family after another hospitalization, Kurt is killed in a motor accident while jogging. In March 2012, his healthy heart is [[Heart transplantation|transplanted]] into Cheney. A few months later, Cheney acquiesces to his daughter Liz's saying she is opposed to same-sex marriage when she runs for a [[2014 United States Senate election in Wyoming|Senate seat in Wyoming]], leaving Mary angry and upset. Liz later [[2016 United States House of Representatives election in Wyoming|wins the election]] to her father's former Congressional position. At the end of the film, an irate Cheney breaks the [[fourth wall]] and delivers a monologue to the audience, stating that he has no regrets about anything he has done in his career.\n\nA [[post-credits scene|mid-credits scene]] depicts a focus group descending into chaos when a conservative panelist slams the film itself as biased and attacks a liberal panelist who defends the movie and insults him, while another younger panelist expresses her anticipation for the next ''[[Fast & Furious|The Fast and the Furious]]'' movie.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main characters===\n{{cast list|\n* [[Christian Bale]] as [[Dick Cheney]]\n** Alex MacNicoll and Aidan Gail as young Dick Cheney\n* [[Amy Adams]] as [[Lynne Cheney|Lynne Vincent Cheney]]\n** [[Cailee Spaeny]] as young Lynne\n* [[Steve Carell]] as [[Donald Rumsfeld]]\n* [[Sam Rockwell]] as [[George W. Bush]]\n* [[Tyler Perry]] as [[Colin Powell]]\n* [[Alison Pill]] as [[Mary Cheney]]\n** Colyse Harger as young Mary Cheney\n* [[Lily Rabe]] as [[Liz Cheney]]\n** Violet Hicks as young Liz Cheney\n* [[Jesse Plemons]] as Kurt, the narrator\n}}\n\n===Supporting characters===\n{{cast list|\n* [[Justin Kirk]] as [[Scooter Libby]]\n* [[LisaGay Hamilton]] as [[Condoleezza Rice]]\n* [[Eddie Marsan]] as [[Paul Wolfowitz]]\n* [[Bill Camp]] as [[Gerald Ford]]\n* [[Don McManus]] as [[David Addington]]\n* [[Shea Whigham]] as Wayne Vincent\n* [[Stephen Adly Guirgis]] as [[George Tenet]]\n* Josh Latzer as Secret Service Agent\n* Vishesh Chachra as Secret Service Agent Robert\n* Jeff Bosley as Secret Service Agent\n* Camille Harman as [[Mary Matalin]]\n* [[Jillian Armenante]] as [[Karen Hughes]]\n* [[Matthew Jacobs]] as [[Antonin Scalia]]\n** Sam Massaro as young Scalia\n* Robert Hughes as [[Warren E. Burger]]\n* [[Paul Perri]] as [[Trent Lott]]\n* [[Brandon Sklenar]] as Bobby Prentace\n* [[Fay Masterson]] as Edna Vincent\n* Kyle More as [[Roger Ailes]]\n* [[Kirk Bovill]] as [[Henry Kissinger]]\n* Melissa K. Marks as [[Mary Cheney#Personal life|Heather Poe]]\n* Chris Dougherty as [[Philip Perry]]\n* John Hillner as [[George H. W. Bush]]\n* [[Michael Reilly Burke]] as David Gribbin\n* William Goldman as [[Dennis Hastert]]\n* Tony Forsmark as [[Grover Norquist]]\n* [[Adam Bartley]] as [[Frank Luntz]]\n* Kevin J. Flood as [[Richard A. Clarke]]\n* Paul Yoo as [[John Yoo]]\n* [[Brandon Firla]] as [[Jay Bybee]]\n* Matt Champagne as [[Douglas J. Feith]]\n* Joseph Beck as [[Karl Rove]]\n* Tony Graham as [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]]\n* Alex Kingi as [[Osama bin Laden]]\n* David Fabrizio as [[Lawrence Wilkerson]]\n* Mark Bramhall as [[Harry Whittington]]\n* James Hornbeck as [[Patrick Leahy]]\n* [[Alfred Molina]] as Waiter (uncredited)\n* [[Naomi Watts]] as News Anchor (uncredited)\n}}\n\n==Production==\nOn November 22, 2016, it was announced that [[Paramount Pictures]] had come on board to handle the rights to a drama about Dick Cheney; the screenplay was to be written by [[Adam McKay]], who would also direct.<ref name=\"Nov2016D\">{{cite news |first=Mike Jr.|last=Fleming|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/adam-mckay-dick-cheney-movie-vice-president-george-w-bush-the-big-short-paramount-pictures-1201858665|title=Adam McKay To Direct Dick Cheney Movie At Paramount|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |location=Los Angeles, California|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=November 23, 2016}}</ref> The film was produced by Plan B producers [[Brad Pitt]], [[Dede Gardner]] and [[Jeremy Kleiner]], along with McKay and his Gary Sanchez partners [[Will Ferrell]] and Kevin Messick.<ref name=\"Nov2016D\"/> Bale signed on to play Cheney in April 2017, and gained 40 pounds (18&nbsp;kg) for the role.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jake|last=Coyle |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/christian-bale-to-play-dick-cheney-in-adam-mckays-biopic|title=Christian Bale to play Dick Cheney in Adam McKay\u2019s biopic|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|publisher=Seattle Times Company|location=Seattle, Washington|date=April 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Julie|last=Miller|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/10/christian-bale-dick-cheney-movie|title=See Christian Bale\u2019s Incredible Dick Cheney Transformation in First Vice Photo|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|location=New York City|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 22, [[Bill Pullman]] was cast as [[Nelson Rockefeller]] (though did not appear in the finished film), and a title, ''Backseat'', was announced. It was later changed to ''Vice''.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Dominic|last=Patten|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/bill-pullman-dick-cheney-movie-nelson-rockefeller-casting-adam-mckay-1202154065/|title=Bill Pullman Joins Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Movie As A Veep Himself|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 22, 2017|access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> On August 31, Sam Rockwell was cast as George W. Bush.<ref>{{cite news|first=Borys|last=Kit|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com//news/sam-rockwell-play-george-w-bush-adam-mckays-dick-cheney-biopic-1034341 |title=Sam Rockwell to Play George W. Bush in Adam McKay's Dick Cheney Biopic (Exclusive) |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 31, 2017|access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Adam Bartley joined the cast.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Amanda |last=N'Duka|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/adam-bartley-adam-mckay-dick-cheney-film-elaine-hendrix-burying-yasmeen-1202173129/|title=Adam Bartley Joins Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Film; Elaine Hendrix Cast In \u2018Burying Yasmeen\u2019 Indie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal production commenced in late September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Dave|last=McNary|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/sam-rockwell-george-w-bush-cheney-movie-1202544347/|title=Sam Rockwell in Talks to Play George W. Bush in Adam McKay\u2019s \u2018Cheney\u2019|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 31, 2017|access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> Tyler Perry and Lily Rabe joined the film in October as Colin Powell and Liz Cheney, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike Jr.|last=Fleming |url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/tyler-perry-colin-powell-dick-cheney-movie-christian-bale-adam-mckay-annapurna-1202185903 |title=Tyler Perry To Play Colin Powell In Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Pic |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |location=Los Angeles, California|date=October 10, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Anita|last=Busch |url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/lily-rabe-liz-cheney-annapurna-dick-cheney-movie-annapurna-1202187167/ |title=Lily Rabe Will Portray Liz Cheney In Annapurna Feature About Dick Cheney|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=October 12, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe official [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]] was released on October 3, 2018.<ref name=\"trailer1\">{{Cite news|first=Margeaux|last=Sippell |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/vice-trailer-christian-bale-dick-cheney-1202966136/|title=Christian Bale Transforms Into Dick Cheney in \u2018Vice\u2019 First Trailer (Watch)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=October 3, 2018 |access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Samuel Goldwyn Theater]] in [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]] on December 11, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|first=Matthew|last=St. Clair |url=https://www.usatoday.com/picture-gallery/life/movies/2018/12/12/vice-stars-were-red-carpet-world-premiere-la/2285182002|title='Vice': Stars were on the red carpet for the world premiere in LA|website=[[USA Today]]|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Vice'' was released in both Canada and the United States on December 25, 2018<ref>{{cite web|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/adam-mckays-dick-cheney-project-now-titled-vice-1202473025|title=Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Project Now Titled \u2018Vice\u2019; Will Go Wide On Christmas Day|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 28, 2018|accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"trailer1\"/> alongside ''[[Holmes & Watson]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-wednesday-box-office-second-weekend-projection-vice-holmes-watson-1202526448/|title=\u2018Aquaman\u2019 $16.9M Wednesday Bests \u2018Last Jedi\u2019 & \u2018Black Panther\u2019; DC Superhero Will Fly To $54M Second Weekend|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 27, 2018|website=Deadline|access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref> It was previously scheduled for release on December 14, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/christian-bale-dick-cheney-adam-mckay-sorry-to-bother-you-sundance-release-dates-movies-1202283248/|title=Annapurna Dates Films By Adam McKay, Babak Anvari & Sundance Acquisition \u2018Sorry To Bother You\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=February 9, 2018|accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> The film opened in the [[United Kingdom|U.K.]] on January 25, 2019, with most of [[Europe]] and [[Hong Kong]] following with February 2019 [[Art release#Film|release dates]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.imdb.com/title/tt6266538/releaseinfo|title=''Vice Release Info''|website=IMDb|access-date=January 5, 2019}} {{better source|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Vice'' was released on [[Blu-ray|Blu-ray Disc]] and DVD by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] on April 16, 2019.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Vice'' grossed $47.8 million in the United States and Canada, and $28.2 million in other territories, for a total worldwide gross of $76.1 million, against a production budget of $60 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[Holmes & Watson]]'' on Christmas Day and was projected to gross around $13 million from 2,378 theaters over its first six days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-bumblebee-mary-poppins-returns-jennifer-lopez-christmas-box-office-1202522277|title=\u2018Aquaman\u2019 Darting To $120M+ In Competitive Christmas 5-Day Corridor \u2013 Box Office Preview|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 18, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-wednesday-box-office-second-weekend-projection-vice-holmes-watson-1202526448|title='Aquaman\u2019 $16.9M Wednesday Bests \u2018Last Jedi\u2019 & \u2018Black Panther\u2019; DC Superhero Will Fly To $54M Second Weekend|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 27, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> It made $4.8 million on its first day and $2.9 million on its second.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-bumblebee-christmas-thursday-night-previews-weekend-box-office-1202524462|title='Aquaman\u2019 Unwraps $22M+ On Christmas For $105M+ Cume; \u2018Holmes & Watson\u2019 Opens To $6M+; \u2018Vice\u2019 $4M+|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 26, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> The film went on to have a first weekend gross of $7.8 million, for a six-day total of $17.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-mary-poppins-returns-bumblebee-new-years-weekend-box-office-1202526812|title='Aquaman\u2019 Sailing To $52M+ 2nd Weekend; $189M+ Cume Pacing Ahead Of \u2018Doctor Strange\u2019 & \u2018Guardians Of The Galaxy\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 30, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> According to ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', the film performed its \"best on both coasts, versus America's heartland, although some theaters in markets including [[Dallas]], [[Houston]] and [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] turned in respectable business\".<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-basis-sex-vice-lure-liberal-moviegoers-1172001 Specialty Box Office: 'On the Basis of Sex', 'Vice' Lure Urban Liberal Moviegoers]</ref> It then made $5.8 million in its second weekend and $3.3 million in its third.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/aquaman-escape-room-weekend-box-office-first-weekend-2019-1202529013/|title=\u2018Aquaman\u2019 Still The Big Man At The B.O. With $30M+; \u2018Escape Room\u2019 Packs In $17M+ \u2013 Early Sunday Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 6, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/kevin-hart-the-upside-aquaman-keanu-reeves-replicas-dogs-way-home-weekend-box-office-1202533526/|title=\u2018Upside\u2019 Set To Be STX\u2019s First No. 1 Opener With $19M+; \u2018Aquaman\u2019 Flips Over $1B WW; Keanu Reeves Hits B.O. Low With \u2018Replicas\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 13, 2018|first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 66% based on 341 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 6.69/10. The website's critical consensus reads: \"''Vice'' takes scattershot aim at its targets, but writer-director Adam McKay hits some satisfying bullseyes\u2014and Christian Bale's transformation is a sight to behold.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/vice_2018|title=Vice (2018)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score 61 out of 100, based on 54 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/vice-2018|title=Vice Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C+\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an overall positive score of 72% and a 49% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=opening /> The critical response to ''Vice'' made it one of the worst-reviewed films to ever be nominated for Best Picture at the [[Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.thewrap.com/adam-mckay-dick-cheney-biopic-vice-polarizes-critics-christian-bale/ | title=Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Biopic \u2018Vice\u2019 Polarizes Critics, From \u2018Clunky\u2019 to \u2018Zeitgeist Event\u2019| work=[[thewrap]] | date=December 17, 2018 | accessdate=December 17, 2018 | first=Brian| last=Welk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.thedailybeast.com/oscars-are-bohemian-rhapsody-and-vice-the-worst-best-picture-nominees-ever | title=Oscars: Are \u2018Bohemian Rhapsody\u2019 and \u2018Vice\u2019 the Worst Best Picture Nominees Ever?| work=[[The Daily Beast]] | date=January 22, 2019 | accessdate=January 26, 2019 | first=Kevin | last=Fallon}}</ref>\n\n[[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', who named the film his favorite of 2018, wrote: \"Across the board in ''Vice'', everyone has risen to the occasion of their individual challenges, none of them easy, to collectively pull off a political satire that both provokes great laughs and hits home with some tragic truths\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Todd|last=McCarthy|authorlink=Todd McCarthy|date=December 17, 2018 |title=\u2018Vice\u2019: Film Review|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/vice-review-1166477|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref> Eric Kohn of [[IndieWire]] gave the film a \"B\u2013\" and called it \"messy but ambitious\", writing: \"''Vice'', in its rambunctious and unfocused manner, takes some ludicrous risks to make cogent points about Cheney's malicious intent\u2014and how he put his plans into action\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric|last=Kohn |date=December 17, 2018 |title=\u2018Vice\u2019 Review: Christian Bale Is a Perfect Dick Cheney, But the Satire Tries Too Hard|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/12/vice-review-christian-bale-dick-cheney-1202027625/|website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref> By contrast, [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' awarded the film 4/5 stars, and wrote that Bale \"captur[es] the former vice-president's bland magnificence in Adam McKay's entertainingly nihilist biopic\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bradshaw |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Bradshaw |title=Vice review \u2013 Christian Bale hilarious as toad-like VP Dick Cheney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/dec/17/vice-review-christian-bale-dick-cheney-biopic |accessdate=January 1, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' film critic [[Peter Travers]] praised the film, giving it a 4/5 rating and writing: \"Adam McKay's flamethrowing take on Dick Cheney, played by a shockingly brilliant Christian Bale, polarizes by being ferociously funny one minute, bleakly sorrowful the next, and ready to indict the past in the name of our scarily uncertain future.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Travers |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Travers |title=\u2018Vice\u2019 Review: Meet The Dubya Era\u2019s Dark Lord |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/vice-movie-review-christian-bale-769353 |website=RollingStone.com |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=18 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218012002/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/vice-movie-review-christian-bale-769353/ |archivedate=December 18, 2018 |date=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephanie Zacharek]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' gave the film a negative review, describing ''Vice'' as an \"exhausting film that turns Dick Cheney into a cartoon villain\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephanie|last=Zacharek|authorlink=Stephanie Zacharek|title=Review: An Exhausting Vice Turns Dick Cheney Into a Cartoon Villain|url=http://time.com/5481092/vice-dick-cheney-review|accessdate=January 19, 2019|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]] |location=New York City|date=December 17, 2018}}</ref> ''Ikon London Magazine'', while praising the make-up artistry of [[Greg Cannom]],<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/vice-movie-make-up-artistry-and-costume-design/| title= Vice Movie Make Up Artistry And Costume Design | magazine= Ikon London Magazine | first= Tamara | last= Orlova Alvarez | date= 17 January 2019 | accessdate= 23 January 2019}}</ref> noted that \"the story reminds of a witch hunt\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url= https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/vice-film-review/| title= Vice Film Review | magazine= Ikon London Magazine | first= Tamara | last= Orlova Alvarez | date= 16 January 2019 | accessdate= 23 January 2019}}</ref>\n \n[[Ann Hornaday]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' praised Bale's performance as Cheney but criticized the story pacing, awarding the film 2/5 stars. Hornaday had issues with the film's structure, writing that the film is \"a mess, zigging here and zagging there, never knowing quite when to end, and when it finally does, leaving few penetrating or genuinely illuminating ideas to ponder\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hornaday|first1=Ann|authorlink1=Ann Hornaday|title=Christian Bale nails it as Dick Cheney in 'Vice', but the rest of the movie is an absurd mess|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/christian-bale-nails-it-as-dick-cheney-in-vice-but-the-rest-of-the-movie-is-an-absurd-mess/2018/12/18/948931ba-fe58-11e8-ad40-cdfd0e0dd65a_story.html|accessdate=January 19, 2019|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> Similarly, Scott Mendelson of ''[[Forbes]]'' praised Bale's and [[Amy Adams]]'s performances, but criticized the film as a \"cinematic mediocrity\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mendelson|first1=Scott|title='Vice' Review: Strong Performances Can't Save Useless Dick Cheney Biopic|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/12/17/vice-review-dick-cheney-christian-bale-amy-adams-adam-mckay-george-w-bush/#3f45c9383895|accessdate=January 19, 2019|magazine=[[Forbes]]|publisher=[[Forbes Media]]|location=New York City|date=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Responses from Cheney family===\nDick Cheney's daughter and Congresswoman [[Liz Cheney]] criticized Christian Bale for his portrayal of her father in ''Vice'', remarking during a ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' interview that \"he finally had the chance to play a real superhero, and he clearly screwed it up\". Liz also responded negatively to Bale's controversial acceptance speech for winning the best actor in a comedy or musical Golden Globe for his portrayal of Dick Cheney, in which the actor thanked Satan for inspiring him to play the role of Cheney.<ref>{{YouTube|id=5LkHkRXqOEI|title=Cheney speaks out on Christian Bale calling her dad 'satan' }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/liz-cheney-says-christian-bale-blew-his-chance-to-play-a-real-superhero--her-father/2019/01/09/1a11ff7a-1410-11e9-b6ad-9cfd62dbb0a8_story.html|title=Liz Cheney says Christian Bale blew his chance to play \u2018a real superhero\u2019 \u2014 her father|last1=Wagner|first1=John|date=9 January 2019|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://fortune.com/2019/01/09/liz-cheney-christian-bale-vice/|title=Liz Cheney Says Christian Bale 'Screwed Up' His Chance to Play \u2018a Real Superhero\u2019 in Movie About Her Dad|last1=Stampler|first1=Laura|date=9 January 2019|work=Fortune|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Vice (2018 film)}}\n''Vice'' was nominated for six [[Golden Globe Awards]] at the [[76th Golden Globe Awards|76th annual ceremony]], the most nominations of any film,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|date=6 December 2018|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> with Bale winning for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=All the Winners of the 76th Golden Globes|date=6 January 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075|website=[[Golden Globe Awards]]}}</ref> The film was subsequently nominated for eight awards at the [[91st Academy Awards]] (winning [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Make-Up and Hairstyling]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/22/entertainment/oscar-nominations-2019/index.html|title=Oscars 2019: See who's nominated|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|work=[[CNN]]|first=Lisa Respers|last=France}}</ref> nine awards at the [[24th Critics' Choice Awards]] (winning [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor in a Comedy|Best Actor in a Comedy]] for Bale),<ref>{{cite news|date=13 January 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://6abc.com/entertainment/full-list-of-critics-choice-awards-winners/5070843/|title=Critics' Choice Awards winners: Full list of Critics' Choice Award winners|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|publisher=6abc}}</ref> and six awards at the [[72nd British Academy Film Awards]] (winning [[BAFTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]).<ref>{{cite web|title='The Favourite' Dominates BAFTA Nominations 2019|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/bafta-awards-nominations-2019-complete-list-1172383|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 9, 2019|accessdate=January 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109102431/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/bafta-awards-nominations-2019-complete-list-1172383|archive-date=January 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, the film was nominated for [[Cinema for Peace]]'s Most Valuable Film of the Year award 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2019|title=Nominations 2019|website=Cinema for Peace Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Federal Advisory Committee Act]]\n*[[Unitary executive theory]]\n*[[Neoconservatism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official site|https://www.vice.movie/home/}}\n* {{IMDb title|6266538}}\n* {{Metacritic film|vice-2018}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|m/vice_2018}}\n* {{Mojo title|dickcheneyfilm}}\n\n{{Adam McKay}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s biographical films]]\n[[Category:2010s black comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:2010s satirical films]]\n[[Category:American biographical films]]\n[[Category:American black comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American political drama films]]\n[[Category:American LGBT-related films]]\n[[Category:American nonlinear narrative films]]\n[[Category:American satirical films]]\n[[Category:Annapurna Pictures films]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:Comedy films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George H. W. Bush]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George W. Bush]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Gerald Ford]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Henry Kissinger]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Richard Nixon]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Osama bin Laden]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Dick Cheney]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about George W. Bush]]\n[[Category:Films based on the September 11 attacks]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Adam McKay]]\n[[Category:Films featuring a Best Musical or Comedy Actor Golden Globe winning performance]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Adam McKay]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Brad Pitt]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Megan Ellison]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Will Ferrell]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Nicholas Britell]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1963]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1968]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1980s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 1990s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2010s]]\n[[Category:Films set in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Films set in the White House]]\n[[Category:Films set in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Films set in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Films set in Wyoming]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Academy Award for Best Makeup]]\n[[Category:Gary Sanchez Productions films]]\n[[Category:Plan B Entertainment films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 American biographical drama film by Adam McKay}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Vice\n| image          = Vice (2018 film poster).png\n| alt            =\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Adam McKay]]\n| producer       = {{plainlist|\n* [[Brad Pitt]]\n* [[Dede Gardner]]\n* [[Jeremy Kleiner]]\n* Kevin J. Messick\n* [[Will Ferrell]]\n* Adam McKay\n}}\n| writer         = Adam McKay\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Christian Bale]]\n* [[Amy Adams]]\n* [[Steve Carell]]\n* [[Sam Rockwell]]\n* [[Tyler Perry]]\n* [[Alison Pill]]\n* [[Lily Rabe]]\n* [[Jesse Plemons]]\n}}<!--PER BILLING BLOCK http://www.impawards.com/2018/vice_ver3.html-->\n| music          = [[Nicholas Britell]]\n| cinematography = [[Greig Fraser]]\n| editing        = [[Hank Corwin]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Plan B Entertainment]]\n* [[Gary Sanchez Productions]]\n* [[Annapurna Pictures]]\n}}\n| distributor    = Annapurna Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|12|11|[[Samuel Goldwyn Theater]]|2018|12|25|United States}}\n| runtime        = 132 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $60 million<ref>{{cite web|title=The Reasons Behind Annapurna\u2019s Tumultuous Week|url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/annapurna-shakeup-reasons-james-bond-roger-ailes-jennifer-lopez-megan-ellison-analysis-1202480157/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Anthony D'Alessandro |date=October 10, 2018|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Annapurna>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/welcome/2702210/single/~annapurna-upheaval-megan-ellison-reevaluating-film-division~/|title=Annapurna Upheaval: Megan Ellison Is \u2018Reevaluating\u2019 Film Division Amid Money Woes|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=October 10, 2018|accessdate=October 10, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $76.1 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|title=Vice (2018) |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=dickcheneyfilm.htm|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=May 10, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Vice''''' is a 2018 American [[biographical film|biographical]] [[drama]] film written and directed by [[Adam McKay]]. The film stars [[Christian Bale]] as former [[Vice President of the United States|U.S. Vice President]] [[Dick Cheney]],<ref name=\"Bale\">{{cite web|url=http://pagesix.com/2017/04/12/christian-bale-cast-as-dick-cheney-in-biopic/|title=Christian Bale cast as Dick Cheney in biopic|magazine=[[Page Six]]|date=April 12, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> with [[Amy Adams]], [[Steve Carell]], [[Sam Rockwell]], [[Justin Kirk]], [[Tyler Perry]], [[Alison Pill]], [[Lily Rabe]], and [[Jesse Plemons]] in supporting roles. The film follows Cheney on his path to become the most powerful [[List of vice presidents of the United States|Vice President]] in American history.<ref>{{cite web|first=Chris|last=Agar|url=https://screenrant.com/dick-cheney-biopic-george-bush-actor-cast/|title=Dick Cheney Biopic: George W. Bush Actor & More Revealed|website=[[Screen Rant]]|publisher=Valnet, Inc.|location=Montreal, Quebec, Canada|date=August 18, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Dominic|last=Patten|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/bill-pullman-dick-cheney-movie-nelson-rockefeller-casting-adam-mckay-1202154065/|title=Bill Pullman joins Jeff Bridges' Dick Cheney movie as a veep himself|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 22, 2017|accessdate=September 3, 2017}}</ref> It is the second theatrical film to depict the [[presidency of George W. Bush]], following [[Oliver Stone]]'s ''[[W. (film)|W.]]'' (2008).\n\n''Vice'' was released in the United States on December 25, 2018, by [[Annapurna Pictures]], and grossed $76 million worldwide. Despite the performances of the cast (particularly Bale, Adams and Rockwell) receiving universal acclaim, the film polarized critics; some considered it to be one of the best films of the year while others thought it to be one of the worst, with McKay's screenplay and direction receiving both \"scathing critiques and celebratory praise\". <ref>{{cite web|first=Nate|last=Nickolai|date=December 17, 2018|title=\u2018Vice\u2019 Reviews: What the Critics Are Saying|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/vice-reviews-critics-christian-bale-adam-mckay-1203091272|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=New York City|accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Alison|last=Foreman|date=December 17, 2018|title=\u2018VICE' divides critics in early reviews|url=https://mashable.com/article/vice-review-roundup-christian-bale-dick-cheney/#FywJb4QPPOqR|work=[[Mashable]]|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film received [[List of accolades received by Vice (2018 film)|numerous awards and nominations]], with eight nominations at the [[91st Academy Awards]], including a [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] nomination and a win for [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Make-Up and Hairstyling]]. It also had a leading six nominations at the [[76th Golden Globe Awards]] (including a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Musical or Comedy]]), and six nominations at the [[72nd British Academy Film Awards]]. For their performances, Bale, Adams, and Rockwell were nominated at all three shows, with Bale winning the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]].\n\n==Plot==\n''Vice'' is narrated by Kurt, a fictitious veteran of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] and [[Iraq War]]s. The film opens with [[Dick Cheney]] and other [[White House]] officials and staff responding to the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]]. The film then flashes back to [[Wyoming]] in 1963, where Cheney finds work as a [[lineworker|lineman]] after his alcoholism led him to drop out of [[Yale University]]. After Cheney is stopped by a traffic cop for [[Driving under the influence|driving while intoxicated]], his wife [[Lynne Cheney]] convinces him to clean up his life.\n\nThe film flashes forward to 1969 when Cheney finds work as a White House intern during the [[Presidency of Richard Nixon|Nixon Administration]]. Working under Nixon's economic adviser, [[Donald Rumsfeld]], Cheney becomes a savvy political operative as he juggles commitments to his wife and their daughters, [[Liz Cheney|Liz]] and [[Mary Cheney|Mary]]. Cheney overhears [[Henry Kissinger]] discussing the secret [[Operation Menu|bombing of Cambodia]] with [[President of the United States|President]] [[Richard Nixon]], revealing the true power of the [[Federal government of the United States#Executive branch|executive branch]] to Cheney. Rumsfeld's abrasive attitude leads to him and Cheney being distanced from Nixon, which works in both men's favor; after [[Richard Nixon's resignation speech|Nixon's resignation]], Cheney rises to the position of [[White House Chief of Staff]] for President [[Gerald Ford]] while Rumsfeld becomes [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]]. The media later dubs the sudden shake-up in the [[Cabinet of the United States|cabinet]] as the [[Halloween Massacre]]. During his tenure, a young [[Antonin Scalia]] introduces Cheney to the [[unitary executive theory]].\n\nAfter [[1976 United States presidential election|Ford is voted out of office]], Cheney runs to be [[1978 United States House of Representatives election in Wyoming|representative for Wyoming]]. After giving an awkward and uncharismatic campaign speech, Cheney suffers his first [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]]. While he recovers, Lynne campaigns on her husband's behalf, helping him to win a seat in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]]. During the [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|Reagan Administration]], Cheney supported a raft of conservative, pro-business policies favoring the [[fossil fuel]] industries. He also supported the abolishment of the [[FCC fairness doctrine]] which led to the rise of [[Fox News]], [[conservative talk radio]], and the rising level of [[Political polarization|party polarization]] in the United States. Cheney next serves as [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] under President [[George H. W. Bush]] during the [[Gulf War]]. Outside of politics, Cheney and Lynne come to terms with their younger daughter, Mary, [[coming out]] as [[lesbian]]. Though Cheney develops ambitions to run for president, he decides to retire from public life to spare Mary from media scrutiny.\n\nDuring the [[presidency of Bill Clinton]], Cheney becomes the CEO of [[Halliburton]] while his wife raises [[Golden Retriever|golden retrievers]] and [[Lynne Cheney#Books|writes books]]. A false epilogue claims that Cheney lived the rest of his life healthy and happy in the private sector and credits begin rolling, only for them to abruptly end as the film continues.\n\nCheney is invited to become running mate to [[George W. Bush]] during the [[2000 United States presidential election]]. Cheney seems to feel that the younger Bush is more interested in pleasing his father than attaining power for himself, Cheney agrees on the condition that Bush delegates \"mundane\" executive responsibilities, such as [[Energy policy of the United States|energy]], the [[United States Armed Forces|military]], and [[Foreign policy of the United States|foreign policy]], to him. As [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]], Cheney works with Secretary of Defense Rumsfeld, legal counsel [[David Addington]], [[Mary Matalin]], and the [[Chief of Staff to the Vice President of the United States|Chief of Staff]], [[Scooter Libby]], to exercise control of key [[Foreign policy of the George W. Bush administration|foreign policy]] and defense decisions throughout Washington.\n\nThe film returns to the aftermath of the September 11 attacks, as Cheney and Rumsfeld maneuver to initiate and then preside over the U.S. invasions [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|of Afghanistan]] and [[2003 invasion of Iraq|Iraq]], resulting in the killing of hundreds of thousands of civilians and the torture of prisoners. As the [[War on terror|War on Terror]] mounts, Cheney continues to struggle with persistent heart attacks. The film also covers various events from his vice presidency, including his endorsement of the unitary executive theory, the [[Plame affair]], the [[Dick Cheney hunting accident|accidental shooting]] of [[Harry Whittington]], and tensions between the Cheney sisters over [[same-sex marriage in the United States|same-sex marriage]]. Cheney's actions are shown to lead to hundreds of thousands of deaths and the rise of the [[Islamic State of Iraq]], resulting in him receiving record-low [[United States presidential approval rating|approval ratings]] by the end of the Bush administration.\n\nWhile narrating Cheney's tearful deathbed goodbye to his family after another hospitalization, Kurt is killed in a motor accident while jogging. In March 2012, his healthy heart is [[Heart transplantation|transplanted]] into Cheney. A few months later, Cheney acquiesces to his daughter Liz's saying she is opposed to same-sex marriage when she runs for a [[2014 United States Senate election in Wyoming|Senate seat in Wyoming]], leaving Mary angry and upset. Liz later [[2016 United States House of Representatives election in Wyoming|wins the election]] to her father's former Congressional position. At the end of the film, an irate Cheney breaks the [[fourth wall]] and delivers a monologue to the audience, stating that he has no regrets about anything he has done in his career.\n\nA [[post-credits scene|mid-credits scene]] depicts a focus group descending into chaos when a conservative panelist slams the film itself as biased and attacks a liberal panelist who defends the movie and insults him, while another younger panelist expresses her anticipation for the next ''[[Fast & Furious|The Fast and the Furious]]'' movie.\n\n==Cast==\n===Main characters===\n{{cast list|\n* [[Christian Bale]] as [[Dick Cheney]]\n** Alex MacNicoll and Aidan Gail as young Dick Cheney\n* [[Amy Adams]] as [[Lynne Cheney|Lynne Vincent Cheney]]\n** [[Cailee Spaeny]] as young Lynne\n* [[Steve Carell]] as [[Donald Rumsfeld]]\n* [[Sam Rockwell]] as [[George W. Bush]]\n* [[Tyler Perry]] as [[Colin Powell]]\n* [[Alison Pill]] as [[Mary Cheney]]\n** Colyse Harger as young Mary Cheney\n* [[Lily Rabe]] as [[Liz Cheney]]\n** Violet Hicks as young Liz Cheney\n* [[Jesse Plemons]] as Kurt, the narrator\n}}\n\n===Supporting characters===\n{{cast list|\n* [[Justin Kirk]] as [[Scooter Libby]]\n* [[LisaGay Hamilton]] as [[Condoleezza Rice]]\n* [[Eddie Marsan]] as [[Paul Wolfowitz]]\n* [[Bill Camp]] as [[Gerald Ford]]\n* [[Don McManus]] as [[David Addington]]\n* [[Shea Whigham]] as Wayne Vincent\n* [[Stephen Adly Guirgis]] as [[George Tenet]]\n* Josh Latzer as Secret Service Agent\n* Vishesh Chachra as Secret Service Agent Robert\n* Jeff Bosley as Secret Service Agent\n* Camille Harman as [[Mary Matalin]]\n* [[Jillian Armenante]] as [[Karen Hughes]]\n* [[Matthew Jacobs]] as [[Antonin Scalia]]\n** Sam Massaro as young Scalia\n* Robert Hughes as [[Warren E. Burger]]\n* [[Paul Perri]] as [[Trent Lott]]\n* [[Brandon Sklenar]] as Bobby Prentace\n* [[Fay Masterson]] as Edna Vincent\n* Kyle More as [[Roger Ailes]]\n* [[Kirk Bovill]] as [[Henry Kissinger]]\n* Melissa K. Marks as [[Mary Cheney#Personal life|Heather Poe]]\n* Chris Dougherty as [[Philip Perry]]\n* John Hillner as [[George H. W. Bush]]\n* [[Michael Reilly Burke]] as David Gribbin\n* William Goldman as [[Dennis Hastert]]\n* Tony Forsmark as [[Grover Norquist]]\n* [[Adam Bartley]] as [[Frank Luntz]]\n* Kevin J. Flood as [[Richard A. Clarke]]\n* Paul Yoo as [[John Yoo]]\n* [[Brandon Firla]] as [[Jay Bybee]]\n* Matt Champagne as [[Douglas J. Feith]]\n* Joseph Beck as [[Karl Rove]]\n* Tony Graham as [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]]\n* Alex Kingi as [[Osama bin Laden]]\n* David Fabrizio as [[Lawrence Wilkerson]]\n* Mark Bramhall as [[Harry Whittington]]\n* James Hornbeck as [[Patrick Leahy]]\n* [[Alfred Molina]] as Waiter (uncredited)\n* [[Naomi Watts]] as News Anchor (uncredited)\n}}\n\n==Production==\nOn November 22, 2016, it was announced that [[Paramount Pictures]] had come on board to handle the rights to a drama about Dick Cheney; the screenplay was to be written by [[Adam McKay]], who would also direct.<ref name=\"Nov2016D\">{{cite news |first=Mike Jr.|last=Fleming|url=https://deadline.com/2016/11/adam-mckay-dick-cheney-movie-vice-president-george-w-bush-the-big-short-paramount-pictures-1201858665|title=Adam McKay To Direct Dick Cheney Movie At Paramount|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |location=Los Angeles, California|date=November 22, 2016|accessdate=November 23, 2016}}</ref> The film was produced by Plan B producers [[Brad Pitt]], [[Dede Gardner]] and [[Jeremy Kleiner]], along with McKay and his Gary Sanchez partners [[Will Ferrell]] and Kevin Messick.<ref name=\"Nov2016D\"/> Bale signed on to play Cheney in April 2017, and gained 40 pounds (18&nbsp;kg) for the role.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jake|last=Coyle |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/nation-world/christian-bale-to-play-dick-cheney-in-adam-mckays-biopic|title=Christian Bale to play Dick Cheney in Adam McKay\u2019s biopic|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|publisher=Seattle Times Company|location=Seattle, Washington|date=April 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|first=Julie|last=Miller|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2018/10/christian-bale-dick-cheney-movie|title=See Christian Bale\u2019s Incredible Dick Cheney Transformation in First Vice Photo|magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|location=New York City|date=October 2, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn August 22, [[Bill Pullman]] was cast as [[Nelson Rockefeller]] (though did not appear in the finished film), and a title, ''Backseat'', was announced. It was later changed to ''Vice''.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Dominic|last=Patten|url=https://deadline.com/2017/08/bill-pullman-dick-cheney-movie-nelson-rockefeller-casting-adam-mckay-1202154065/|title=Bill Pullman Joins Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Movie As A Veep Himself|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 22, 2017|access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> On August 31, Sam Rockwell was cast as George W. Bush.<ref>{{cite news|first=Borys|last=Kit|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com//news/sam-rockwell-play-george-w-bush-adam-mckays-dick-cheney-biopic-1034341 |title=Sam Rockwell to Play George W. Bush in Adam McKay's Dick Cheney Biopic (Exclusive) |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Eldridge Industries]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 31, 2017|access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Adam Bartley joined the cast.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Amanda |last=N'Duka|url=https://deadline.com/2017/09/adam-bartley-adam-mckay-dick-cheney-film-elaine-hendrix-burying-yasmeen-1202173129/|title=Adam Bartley Joins Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Film; Elaine Hendrix Cast In \u2018Burying Yasmeen\u2019 Indie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 19, 2017|access-date=January 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal production commenced in late September 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Dave|last=McNary|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/sam-rockwell-george-w-bush-cheney-movie-1202544347/|title=Sam Rockwell in Talks to Play George W. Bush in Adam McKay\u2019s \u2018Cheney\u2019|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=August 31, 2017|access-date=September 19, 2017}}</ref> Tyler Perry and Lily Rabe joined the film in October as Colin Powell and Liz Cheney, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike Jr.|last=Fleming |url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/tyler-perry-colin-powell-dick-cheney-movie-christian-bale-adam-mckay-annapurna-1202185903 |title=Tyler Perry To Play Colin Powell In Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Pic |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |location=Los Angeles, California|date=October 10, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Anita|last=Busch |url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/lily-rabe-liz-cheney-annapurna-dick-cheney-movie-annapurna-1202187167/ |title=Lily Rabe Will Portray Liz Cheney In Annapurna Feature About Dick Cheney|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=October 12, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe official [[Trailer (promotion)|trailer]] was released on October 3, 2018.<ref name=\"trailer1\">{{Cite news|first=Margeaux|last=Sippell |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/vice-trailer-christian-bale-dick-cheney-1202966136/|title=Christian Bale Transforms Into Dick Cheney in \u2018Vice\u2019 First Trailer (Watch)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=October 3, 2018 |access-date=2018-10-06}}</ref> The film premiered at the [[Samuel Goldwyn Theater]] in [[Beverly Hills, California|Beverly Hills]] on December 11, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|first=Matthew|last=St. Clair |url=https://www.usatoday.com/picture-gallery/life/movies/2018/12/12/vice-stars-were-red-carpet-world-premiere-la/2285182002|title='Vice': Stars were on the red carpet for the world premiere in LA|website=[[USA Today]]|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Vice'' was released in both Canada and the United States on December 25, 2018<ref>{{cite web|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/adam-mckays-dick-cheney-project-now-titled-vice-1202473025|title=Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Project Now Titled \u2018Vice\u2019; Will Go Wide On Christmas Day|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=September 28, 2018|accessdate=September 28, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"trailer1\"/> alongside ''[[Holmes & Watson]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-wednesday-box-office-second-weekend-projection-vice-holmes-watson-1202526448/|title=\u2018Aquaman\u2019 $16.9M Wednesday Bests \u2018Last Jedi\u2019 & \u2018Black Panther\u2019; DC Superhero Will Fly To $54M Second Weekend|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 27, 2018|website=Deadline|access-date=September 1, 2019}}</ref> It was previously scheduled for release on December 14, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/christian-bale-dick-cheney-adam-mckay-sorry-to-bother-you-sundance-release-dates-movies-1202283248/|title=Annapurna Dates Films By Adam McKay, Babak Anvari & Sundance Acquisition \u2018Sorry To Bother You\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=February 9, 2018|accessdate=January 19, 2019}}</ref> The film opened in the [[United Kingdom|U.K.]] on January 25, 2019, with most of [[Europe]] and [[Hong Kong]] following with February 2019 [[Art release#Film|release dates]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://m.imdb.com/title/tt6266538/releaseinfo|title=''Vice Release Info''|website=IMDb|access-date=January 5, 2019}} {{better source|date=October 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Vice'' was released on [[Blu-ray|Blu-ray Disc]] and DVD by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] on April 16, 2019.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Vice'' grossed $47.8 million in the United States and Canada, and $28.2 million in other territories, for a total worldwide gross of $76.1 million, against a production budget of $60 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[Holmes & Watson]]'' on Christmas Day and was projected to gross around $13 million from 2,378 theaters over its first six days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-bumblebee-mary-poppins-returns-jennifer-lopez-christmas-box-office-1202522277|title=\u2018Aquaman\u2019 Darting To $120M+ In Competitive Christmas 5-Day Corridor \u2013 Box Office Preview|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 18, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-wednesday-box-office-second-weekend-projection-vice-holmes-watson-1202526448|title='Aquaman\u2019 $16.9M Wednesday Bests \u2018Last Jedi\u2019 & \u2018Black Panther\u2019; DC Superhero Will Fly To $54M Second Weekend|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 27, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 28, 2018}}</ref> It made $4.8 million on its first day and $2.9 million on its second.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-bumblebee-christmas-thursday-night-previews-weekend-box-office-1202524462|title='Aquaman\u2019 Unwraps $22M+ On Christmas For $105M+ Cume; \u2018Holmes & Watson\u2019 Opens To $6M+; \u2018Vice\u2019 $4M+|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 26, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 26, 2018}}</ref> The film went on to have a first weekend gross of $7.8 million, for a six-day total of $17.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/aquaman-mary-poppins-returns-bumblebee-new-years-weekend-box-office-1202526812|title='Aquaman\u2019 Sailing To $52M+ 2nd Weekend; $189M+ Cume Pacing Ahead Of \u2018Doctor Strange\u2019 & \u2018Guardians Of The Galaxy\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 30, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=December 30, 2018}}</ref> According to ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', the film performed its \"best on both coasts, versus America's heartland, although some theaters in markets including [[Dallas]], [[Houston]] and [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] turned in respectable business\".<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-basis-sex-vice-lure-liberal-moviegoers-1172001 Specialty Box Office: 'On the Basis of Sex', 'Vice' Lure Urban Liberal Moviegoers]</ref> It then made $5.8 million in its second weekend and $3.3 million in its third.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/aquaman-escape-room-weekend-box-office-first-weekend-2019-1202529013/|title=\u2018Aquaman\u2019 Still The Big Man At The B.O. With $30M+; \u2018Escape Room\u2019 Packs In $17M+ \u2013 Early Sunday Update|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 6, 2018|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/kevin-hart-the-upside-aquaman-keanu-reeves-replicas-dogs-way-home-weekend-box-office-1202533526/|title=\u2018Upside\u2019 Set To Be STX\u2019s First No. 1 Opener With $19M+; \u2018Aquaman\u2019 Flips Over $1B WW; Keanu Reeves Hits B.O. Low With \u2018Replicas\u2019|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=January 13, 2018|first=Anthony |last=D'Alessandro |accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 66% based on 341 reviews, with an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average rating]] of 6.69/10. The website's critical consensus reads: \"''Vice'' takes scattershot aim at its targets, but writer-director Adam McKay hits some satisfying bullseyes\u2014and Christian Bale's transformation is a sight to behold.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/vice_2018|title=Vice (2018)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|url-status=live|accessdate=September 15, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score 61 out of 100, based on 54 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/vice-2018|title=Vice Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=February 16, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"C+\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an overall positive score of 72% and a 49% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=opening /> The critical response to ''Vice'' made it one of the worst-reviewed films to ever be nominated for Best Picture at the [[Academy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.thewrap.com/adam-mckay-dick-cheney-biopic-vice-polarizes-critics-christian-bale/ | title=Adam McKay\u2019s Dick Cheney Biopic \u2018Vice\u2019 Polarizes Critics, From \u2018Clunky\u2019 to \u2018Zeitgeist Event\u2019| work=[[thewrap]] | date=December 17, 2018 | accessdate=December 17, 2018 | first=Brian| last=Welk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.thedailybeast.com/oscars-are-bohemian-rhapsody-and-vice-the-worst-best-picture-nominees-ever | title=Oscars: Are \u2018Bohemian Rhapsody\u2019 and \u2018Vice\u2019 the Worst Best Picture Nominees Ever?| work=[[The Daily Beast]] | date=January 22, 2019 | accessdate=January 26, 2019 | first=Kevin | last=Fallon}}</ref>\n\n[[Todd McCarthy]] of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'', who named the film his favorite of 2018, wrote: \"Across the board in ''Vice'', everyone has risen to the occasion of their individual challenges, none of them easy, to collectively pull off a political satire that both provokes great laughs and hits home with some tragic truths\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Todd|last=McCarthy|authorlink=Todd McCarthy|date=December 17, 2018 |title=\u2018Vice\u2019: Film Review|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/vice-review-1166477|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref> Eric Kohn of [[IndieWire]] gave the film a \"B\u2013\" and called it \"messy but ambitious\", writing: \"''Vice'', in its rambunctious and unfocused manner, takes some ludicrous risks to make cogent points about Cheney's malicious intent\u2014and how he put his plans into action\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric|last=Kohn |date=December 17, 2018 |title=\u2018Vice\u2019 Review: Christian Bale Is a Perfect Dick Cheney, But the Satire Tries Too Hard|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2018/12/vice-review-christian-bale-dick-cheney-1202027625/|website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref> By contrast, [[Peter Bradshaw]] of ''[[The Guardian]]'' awarded the film 4/5 stars, and wrote that Bale \"captur[es] the former vice-president's bland magnificence in Adam McKay's entertainingly nihilist biopic\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bradshaw |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Bradshaw |title=Vice review \u2013 Christian Bale hilarious as toad-like VP Dick Cheney |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/dec/17/vice-review-christian-bale-dick-cheney-biopic |accessdate=January 1, 2019 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n''[[Rolling Stone]]'' film critic [[Peter Travers]] praised the film, giving it a 4/5 rating and writing: \"Adam McKay's flamethrowing take on Dick Cheney, played by a shockingly brilliant Christian Bale, polarizes by being ferociously funny one minute, bleakly sorrowful the next, and ready to indict the past in the name of our scarily uncertain future.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Travers |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Travers |title=\u2018Vice\u2019 Review: Meet The Dubya Era\u2019s Dark Lord |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/vice-movie-review-christian-bale-769353 |website=RollingStone.com |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]] |accessdate=18 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181218012002/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/vice-movie-review-christian-bale-769353/ |archivedate=December 18, 2018 |date=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Stephanie Zacharek]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' gave the film a negative review, describing ''Vice'' as an \"exhausting film that turns Dick Cheney into a cartoon villain\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephanie|last=Zacharek|authorlink=Stephanie Zacharek|title=Review: An Exhausting Vice Turns Dick Cheney Into a Cartoon Villain|url=http://time.com/5481092/vice-dick-cheney-review|accessdate=January 19, 2019|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]] |location=New York City|date=December 17, 2018}}</ref> ''Ikon London Magazine'', while praising the make-up artistry of [[Greg Cannom]],<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/vice-movie-make-up-artistry-and-costume-design/| title=\u00a0Vice Movie Make Up Artistry And Costume Design | magazine= Ikon London Magazine | first= Tamara | last= Orlova Alvarez | date= 17 January 2019 | accessdate= 23 January 2019}}</ref> noted that \"the story reminds of a witch hunt\".<ref>{{cite magazine | url= https://www.ikonlondonmagazine.com/vice-film-review/| title=\u00a0Vice Film Review | magazine= Ikon London Magazine | first= Tamara | last= Orlova Alvarez | date= 16 January 2019 | accessdate= 23 January 2019}}</ref>\n \n[[Ann Hornaday]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' praised Bale's performance as Cheney but criticized the story pacing, awarding the film 2/5 stars. Hornaday had issues with the film's structure, writing that the film is \"a mess, zigging here and zagging there, never knowing quite when to end, and when it finally does, leaving few penetrating or genuinely illuminating ideas to ponder\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hornaday|first1=Ann|authorlink1=Ann Hornaday|title=Christian Bale nails it as Dick Cheney in 'Vice', but the rest of the movie is an absurd mess|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/christian-bale-nails-it-as-dick-cheney-in-vice-but-the-rest-of-the-movie-is-an-absurd-mess/2018/12/18/948931ba-fe58-11e8-ad40-cdfd0e0dd65a_story.html|accessdate=January 19, 2019|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 18, 2019}}</ref> Similarly, Scott Mendelson of ''[[Forbes]]'' praised Bale's and [[Amy Adams]]'s performances, but criticized the film as a \"cinematic mediocrity\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mendelson|first1=Scott|title='Vice' Review: Strong Performances Can't Save Useless Dick Cheney Biopic|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2018/12/17/vice-review-dick-cheney-christian-bale-amy-adams-adam-mckay-george-w-bush/#3f45c9383895|accessdate=January 19, 2019|magazine=[[Forbes]]|publisher=[[Forbes Media]]|location=New York City|date=December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Responses from Cheney family===\nDick Cheney's daughter and Congresswoman [[Liz Cheney]] criticized Christian Bale for his portrayal of her father in ''Vice'', remarking during a ''[[Fox & Friends]]'' interview that \"he finally had the chance to play a real superhero, and he clearly screwed it up\". Liz also responded negatively to Bale's controversial acceptance speech for winning the best actor in a comedy or musical Golden Globe for his portrayal of Dick Cheney, in which the actor thanked Satan for inspiring him to play the role of Cheney.<ref>{{YouTube|id=5LkHkRXqOEI|title=Cheney speaks out on Christian Bale calling her dad 'satan' }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/liz-cheney-says-christian-bale-blew-his-chance-to-play-a-real-superhero--her-father/2019/01/09/1a11ff7a-1410-11e9-b6ad-9cfd62dbb0a8_story.html|title=Liz Cheney says Christian Bale blew his chance to play \u2018a real superhero\u2019 \u2014 her father|last1=Wagner|first1=John|date=9 January 2019|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://fortune.com/2019/01/09/liz-cheney-christian-bale-vice/|title=Liz Cheney Says Christian Bale 'Screwed Up' His Chance to Play \u2018a Real Superhero\u2019 in Movie About Her Dad|last1=Stampler|first1=Laura|date=9 January 2019|work=Fortune|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{main|List of accolades received by Vice (2018 film)}}\n''Vice'' was nominated for six [[Golden Globe Awards]] at the [[76th Golden Globe Awards|76th annual ceremony]], the most nominations of any film,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|date=6 December 2018|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075/|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> with Bale winning for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy|Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Musical or Comedy]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=All the Winners of the 76th Golden Globes|date=6 January 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2019-1203082075|website=[[Golden Globe Awards]]}}</ref> The film was subsequently nominated for eight awards at the [[91st Academy Awards]] (winning [[Academy Award for Best Makeup and Hairstyling|Best Make-Up and Hairstyling]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/22/entertainment/oscar-nominations-2019/index.html|title=Oscars 2019: See who's nominated|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|work=[[CNN]]|first=Lisa Respers|last=France}}</ref> nine awards at the [[24th Critics' Choice Awards]] (winning [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor in a Comedy|Best Actor in a Comedy]] for Bale),<ref>{{cite news|date=13 January 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://6abc.com/entertainment/full-list-of-critics-choice-awards-winners/5070843/|title=Critics' Choice Awards winners: Full list of Critics' Choice Award winners|location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|publisher=6abc}}</ref> and six awards at the [[72nd British Academy Film Awards]] (winning [[BAFTA Award for Best Editing|Best Editing]]).<ref>{{cite web|title='The Favourite' Dominates BAFTA Nominations 2019|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/bafta-awards-nominations-2019-complete-list-1172383|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 9, 2019|accessdate=January 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190109102431/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/bafta-awards-nominations-2019-complete-list-1172383|archive-date=January 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, the film was nominated for [[Cinema for Peace]]'s Most Valuable Film of the Year award 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinemaforpeace-foundation.org/nominations-2019|title=Nominations 2019|website=Cinema for Peace Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-09}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Federal Advisory Committee Act]]\n*[[Unitary executive theory]]\n*[[Neoconservatism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==